Getting started with PICO:

PICO is a general (parallel) branch-and-bound library which includes a
general mixed-integer-programming (MIP) code.  This MIP code has
branch and cut, but it is not currently working.  It also has no
user-level documentation other than this.  Please ask questions as
they arise as that will help us develop the FAQ and documentation.

This document describes how to check out and maintain PICO and
required libraries using cvs and how to run a simple example MIP
problem.

PICO requires utilib utility library.  This predates STL and has some
things STL does not, (or does them better or more portably).  For more
information on utilib, see http://www.cs.sandia.gov/UTILIB/
(Note: the checkout directions on that page may not be current.  Use
the ones below).

To run the MIP code in PICO, you will also need a linear-programming
solver.  Right now, PICO supports cplex version 7 and soplex.  We use
the COIN OSI interface, but we require some functionality on top of
that provided by OSI.  In principle, though, any LP solver with an OSI
interface can be supported by PICO with a "little" extra effort.  We
maintain a soplex repository and give directions below to use it.  However,
before you check out the code, you must go to the soplex home page
http://www.zib.de/Optimization/Software/Soplex/soplex.php
and acquire your own license.  This is free for academic and research work.

The default configurations assume that all three libraries are in
"sibling" directories.  For example src/pico, src/utilib, and
src/SOPLEX.  Make sure you have installed utilib and one of the lp
libraries before installing PICO.

There are 4 scripts appended to this file (I would have put them in a
shar file, but can't find shar on this system): ssh.cvs, cvs.u, cvs.p,
and cvs.so.  The scripts are delineated with lines like
***** begin cvs.u ****** and
***** end cvs.u ****
Save the four scripts to files (without the **** lines) and make them executable
(eg chmod 755 cvs.u).

To get a copy of utilib, make sure you're in the directory where you'd like
the utilib code tree placed.  Then type

cvs.u -guest utilib checkout

You will be prompted for a password, which is anonymous (that is, the
word "anonymous").

Similar commands (executed in the same directory) will check out pico
(using cvs.p, same password) and soplex (using cvs.so, password: linear!).

Now cd into utilib and run the following two commands:

configure
make install

This should create a library for your system that will work for serial
code.  It also creates symbolic links in the utilib/include directory
to all the header files throughout the code tree.  This is a handy
place to grep if you're looking for a particular method or class.
Utilib has been ported to many platforms and this *should* go through
without problems.

If you want to run PICO in parallel, you will have to configure utilib
(and PICO) to run with MPI.  You have to tell utilib where mpi is on
your machine. To do this, go to the utilib/config directory.  This has
a number of configuration fragments with names like mp-solaris-snl980.
All the mp- files specify where packages (such as mpi or cplex) are.
The second part of the name specifies an operating system and the
third specifies a location.  Find an mp-<your os>-<foo> file and copy
it into mp-<your os>-<name for your site> file.  Then edit the line that
looks like:

MPI_DIR=/Net/proj/opt/packages/SOLARIS/mpich

to specify the location of mpi (mpich) on your machine.

Then go back to the utilib main directory and execute

configure --with-mpi
make clean
make install

(the make clean may not be necessary, but it never hurts).

Installing PICO is similar.  If you choose to use soplex, then
in the main pico directory execute:

configure --with-soplex
make install

As with utilib, you can create an mp-<os>-<your site> file to specify the
location of mpi and/or cplex.  Then configure as
configure --with-mpi --with-soplex

or

configure --with-mpi --with-cplex

etc.

Access through the guest account will not give you permission to modify
utilib or pico through cvs commit commands.  However, you can receive updates via

cvs.u -guest update

run from the main utilib directory (or in a subdirectory if you like).
This will give you bug fixes, new features, etc.  After the update,
it's a good idea to reconfigure and do a clean install.  The text file
config.status in the main utilib directory shows what was used in the
last configuration.  If you just want to reconfigure with the same options, you
can execute

bin/reconfigure
make clean
make install

Of course if you want to change the options, e.g. to change the lp
solver in pico, then you will have to type the reconfigure command
with the appropriate options.

Running PICO:

Installing PICO creates a number of executables in the directory
pico/src/apps/milp

In particular, serialMIP and parMIP run serial and parallel mixed-integer
programming solvers respectively.  The command-line call for a serial run is

serialMIP file.mps -<option>=val ...

The MIP file can be in either mps format (a standard MIP/LP format) or
in lp format.  I think our mps reader is currently more robust.  There
are a number of examples from the standard miplib in

pico/src/etc/mpsfiles/miplib/

This directory includes a file miplib.cat which for most of these
problems has statistics about size, value of the LP relaxation, value
of the optimal integer solution, which variables are integer, binary
vs. general integer, etc.

The remainder of the arguments in the command line can adjust PICO
parameters.  These set constants or strategies within the program such
as tolerances.  All parameters have default values, so you can run
without specifying anything after the mps file.  I'll try to produce
comprehensive documentation for all the command-line parameters ASAP.
In the meantime, you can ask if you think you should be able to tweak
something or you can look for code lines that look like:

CLASS_PARAMETER_DEF(picoBase,statusPrintFrequency,0,1000,MAXDOUBLE);

This defines a parameter called statusPrintFrequency, which controls
the number of subproblem solutions between printing of a status line
(the status line, among other things, tells you the value of the best
solution found so far and the gap between the lower and upper bounds).
This parameter has a default of 1000, a minimum value of 0, and
maximum value of MAXDOUBLE.  So, if you decide you'd rather get status
information every 500 subproblems, you'd run:

serialMIP myprob.mps -statusPrintFrequency=500

You can also specify parameter adjustments in a file but I don't
remember the precise syntax and don't want to hold this up while I
look for it.  If you specify a parameter without a value, the default
is 1 (e.g. for turning on binary options such as using a depth-first search)

serialMIP myprob.mps -depthFirst

To run a parallel instance, you'll have to make sure mpi is set up
properly.  For instance we alias mpirun to

mpirun -machinefile ~/.mpi_machines !*

Then in ~/.mpi_machines you can list the machines to run on in order.
So for, example, if you wish to run on 2 machines, the first two in
the list are used.  Make sure you have configured ssh to allow
password-free login between these machines.

To run a parallel instance, execute

mpirun -np <number-of-machines> parMIP file.mps -<option>=val ...

The solution is put in a file pico-solution.dat in the directory where
you run pico.


